It is unique for erupting natrocarbonatite, a rare and cold type of magma. The Maasai and Sonjo people refer to it as "The Mountain of God", viewing it as the abode of the god Engai, who withdrew there after being hit by a hunter with an arrow. The volcano lies in Tanzania, 16km south of Lake Natron and 120km northwest of Arusha. It is part of the Gregory Rift, an ongoing continental rift extending for 1,200km in eastern and southern Africa. The volcano is part of the Ngorongoro volcanic highland, a system of volcanoes that were active from the Miocene to present, and which includes the Ngorongoro and other volcanoes. Ol Doinyo Lengai is the only presently active volcano of the Gregory Rift. The volcano is continually active, but there are seldom observations of its activity. Threats from Ol Doinyo Lengai eruptions include lahars, landslides, lava flows, pyroclastic flows, volcanic bombs, volcanic gas and volcanic ash fall. Vegetation in the area consists mostly of grassland, which reaches an elevation of 1,750m above sea level. The carbonatite lavas are rapidly chemically modified by rainfall or covered by deposits condensing from fumarolic gases, yielding secondary minerals like calcite, gaylussite, nahcolite, pirssonite, shortite, thermonatrite and trona, including various chlorides, fluorides and sulfates. Ol Doinyo Lengai's magmas appear to form through the separation of carbon-rich phases, with the original magma being variously interpreted to be either nephelinitic or silicic. The eruption was preceded in July by seismic activity, which was frequently mistaken for renewed eruptions, and the intrusion of a dyke less than 20km from Ol Doinyo Lengai. challenge: "Hey there, can you quickly summarize what the South Dakota Air and Space Museum is all about? I'm in a rush and don't have time to read through their entire website."
name: summarization
gpt_reference: The South Dakota Air and Space Museum is dedicated to preserving the history of aviation and space exploration. It showcases over 30 vintage military aircrafts ranging from World War II bombers to modern-day high-speed reconnaissance planes, plus various missiles and spacecraft. The museum offers both indoor exhibits and outdoor airpark tours, providing educational resources and insight into the technology, people, and events that shaped the aviation industry. It's located just outside the main gate of Ellsworth Air Force Base in Box Elder, South Dakota.
goal: summarize the following topic: South Dakota Air and Space Museum
reference: The South Dakota Air and Space Museum, situated in Box Elder near Ellsworth AFB, commemorates the Air Force's history and aviation in South Dakota. Established in 1983 as part of an Air Force program, the museum initially received four former F-89 hangars and a building slated for demolition. The mockup of a Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit from Honda, a restored Boeing B-29 Superfortress, and a Boeing B-47 Stratojet followed. A planned Convair B-36 transfer in 1992 was replaced by a Minuteman II missile silo trainer. In 1998, the museum received a renovation grant, and in 2001, a new entrance with a Rockwell B-1 Lancer was dedicated. The museum showcases displays on aerospace technology, World Wars, the Cold War, aviation pioneers, and Ellsworth AFB. It features training aids like F-106 and B-1B cockpits, an F-16 simulator, and a Minuteman Crew Mission Procedures Trainer. Other exhibits include the Stratobowl Balloon Launches, 44th Bombardment Group/44th Strategic Missile Wing, and the South Dakota Aviation Hall of Fame. The museum's four indoor galleries are named for Frank Hunter, Duke Corning, Clyde Ice, and Joe Foss. In 2017, a Titan I missile was added to the outdoor airpark. The museum also partnered with the Commemorative Air Force to fly a B-25 across South Dakota in 2019.
